    <fullPolicyText>
      <Value><![CDATA[{
  "markup": "<p>Non-exempt employees must be paid for time spent traveling that qualifies as work under the <strong>Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA)</strong> and applicable state regulations. This policy clarifies when travel time is considered compensable.</p>\n<h4>Compensable Travel Time Includes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Travel during the workday</strong>: Time spent traveling between job sites, to and from training, or attending meetings during normal work hours.</li>\n<li><strong>Overnight travel</strong>: Time spent traveling outside of regular working hours as a passenger when the travel is required by the company.</li>\n<li><strong>Travel on non-workdays</strong>: If the travel occurs during hours that would normally be considered work hours on a regular workday, it may be compensable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Non-Compensable Travel Time Includes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Normal commuting</strong>: Travel from home to the regular work location and back is not paid time.</li>\n<li><strong>Voluntary travel</strong>: If you choose to travel for personal convenience or outside of scheduled hours, that time may not be considered compensable.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Employees must accurately record all travel time using approved timekeeping methods. If you’re unsure whether a particular travel period is compensable, please speak with your manager or the HR team for clarification before the travel occurs.</p>\n<p>All travel must be pre-approved, and expense-related policies continue to apply.</p>",
